<subSubSection lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="171" pageId="17" pageNumber="170" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[820,1459,1908,2062]" lastBlockId="18.[129,768,151,240]" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="171" pageId="17" pageNumber="170">
D e s c r i p t i o n a n d r e m a r k s.Chlamydospermous seeds that are four-angled to circular in transverse section, about 
<quantity box="[892,980,1973,1997]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="170" unit="mm" value="0.7">0.7 mm</quantity>
long and 0.55–0.6.5 mm wide. The seed envelope is sclerenchymatic with about 40 slightly raised longitudinal ridges (
<figureCitation box="[1110,1253,2038,2062]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="19.[125,206,1904,1925]" captionTargetBox="[128,1438,151,1884]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Text-fig. 11. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of seeds assigned to the BEG group (a–d) and associated pollen grains (e–i); Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a) Seed of Tomcatia taylorii showing the four horns formed by extensions of the envelope and the central projection of the envelope that surrounds to the micropylar tube; b, c) Seeds of Quadrispermum parvum in lateral (b) and apical (c) views showing the transverse ribs and the central projection of the envelope that surrounds the micropylar tube; d–f) Seeds of Ephedrispermum lusitanicum showing the four-angled seed envelope (d), the micropylar tube surrounded by the tissues of the integument (e), and ephedroid pollen grains on the seed surface (f); g) Apex of seed of Quadrispermum parvum showing simple" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386239" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386239/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="170">Text-fig. 11d</figureCitation>
). Ephedroid pollen grains have been observed in the micropyles of several specimens and also on the surface of the seed envelope (
<figureCitation box="[136,298,215,240]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="19.[125,206,1904,1925]" captionTargetBox="[128,1438,151,1884]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Text-fig. 11. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of seeds assigned to the BEG group (a–d) and associated pollen grains (e–i); Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a) Seed of Tomcatia taylorii showing the four horns formed by extensions of the envelope and the central projection of the envelope that surrounds to the micropylar tube; b, c) Seeds of Quadrispermum parvum in lateral (b) and apical (c) views showing the transverse ribs and the central projection of the envelope that surrounds the micropylar tube; d–f) Seeds of Ephedrispermum lusitanicum showing the four-angled seed envelope (d), the micropylar tube surrounded by the tissues of the integument (e), and ephedroid pollen grains on the seed surface (f); g) Apex of seed of Quadrispermum parvum showing simple" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386239" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386239/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="171">Text-fig. 11e, f</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[128,768,263,607]" pageId="18" pageNumber="171">
A f f i n i t y a n d o t h e r o c c u r r e n c e s. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="RYDIN, K. R. PEDERSEN, P. R. CRANE et E. M. FRIIS" authorityYear="2006" class="Gnetopsida" family="Ephedraceae" genus="Ephedrispermum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gnetales" pageId="18" pageNumber="171" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lusitanicum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="171">Ephedrispermum lusitanicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is common in the Torres Vedras mesofossil flora and also in the mesofossil flora from Buarcos (the 
<typeStatus box="[272,318,359,383]" pageId="18" pageNumber="171">type</typeStatus>
locality for the genus and species). Seeds of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="RYDIN, K. R. PEDERSEN, P. R. CRANE et E. M. FRIIS" authorityYear="2006" box="[163,347,391,415]" class="Gnetopsida" family="Ephedraceae" genus="Ephedrispermum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gnetales" pageId="18" pageNumber="171" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[163,347,391,415]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="171">Ephedrispermum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are also known from the Famalicão and 
<collectingRegion box="[176,223,423,447]" country="Switzerland" name="Valais" pageId="18" pageNumber="171">Vale</collectingRegion>
de Água mesofossil floras, but these seeds differ in having fewer ridges on the seed envelope and in details of the associated pollen grains. The Famalicão and 
<collectingRegion box="[687,734,487,511]" country="Switzerland" name="Valais" pageId="18" pageNumber="171">Vale</collectingRegion>
de Água specimens have been assigned to a separate species 
<taxonomicName authority="E. M. FRIIS, P. R. CRANE et K. R. PEDERSEN (Friis et al. 2019 c)" class="Gnetopsida" family="Ephedraceae" genus="Ephedrispermum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gnetales" pageId="18" pageNumber="171" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tenuicostatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="171">E. tenuicostatum</emphasis>
E.M.FRIIS, P.R.CRANE et K.R.PEDERSEN (
<bibRefCitation author="Friis, E. M. &amp; Crane, P. R. &amp; Pedersen, K. R." pageId="18" pageNumber="171" pagination="643 - 666" refId="ref75954" refString="Friis, E. M., Crane, P. R., Pedersen, K. R. (2019 c): Chla- mydospermous seeds document the diversity and abundance of extinct gnetalean relatives in Early Cretaceous vegetation. - International Journal of Plant Sciences, 180 (7): 643 - 666. https: // doi. org / 10.1086 / 704356" type="journal article" year="2019">Friis et al. 2019c</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
